<header class="hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">The money</div>
    <h1>Who actually <span>paid</span> for this building?</h1>
    <p class="deck">
      The public subsidized it. The tenants paid the mortgage. The tenants made the neighbourhood
      worth something. And all three of those facts are now the reason we're being told we can't
      afford to stay in it.
    </p>
  </div>
</header>

<main class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">

    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Start with what it cost</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      63 Tiffany Place was a failed condo conversion. The developers couldn't sell a single unit,
      because in the early 1990s <strong>nobody wanted to live here.</strong> The building went to
      foreclosure.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      Related Companies bought it at a bank auction for about <strong>$4 million</strong> — a
      70-unit building, so roughly <strong>$57,000 per apartment</strong>. They only made it
      affordable housing because there was no other way to make the property work. In exchange for
      the tax credits, they had to rent to low-income working New Yorkers.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      That's the deal. Public money made a failed building viable. We moved into an area you
      couldn't safely walk around at night, and we stayed.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">Now look at what one tenant paid</h2>
    <p class="lead">This is my own ledger. One apartment. Not the building — <em>one apartment.</em></p>

    <div class="ledger">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="what">
          <b>What Related paid for my apartment</b>
          <span class="sub">$4m auction price ÷ 70 units, 1994</span>
        </div>
        <div class="amt">~$57,000</div>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="what">
          <b>What I paid them in rent</b>
          <span class="sub">Over roughly the first 15 years</span>
        </div>
        <div class="amt red">~$120,000</div>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="what">
          <b>What Irving Langer paid for my apartment</b>
          <span class="sub">$5.3m sale price ÷ 70 units, 2010</span>
        </div>
        <div class="amt">~$75,000</div>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="what">
          <b>What I have paid <em>him</em> in rent</b>
          <span class="sub">Over roughly the next 15 years</span>
        </div>
        <div class="amt red">~$180,000</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pull red" style="margin-top:34px">
      I have paid my landlord roughly two and a half times what he paid for my apartment.
      <span style="display:block;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;margin-top:12px;opacity:.92">
        From one tenant. In fifteen years. Now multiply that by seventy apartments.
      </span>
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      I'm not going to pretend that's a full accounting — there are taxes, there is maintenance,
      there is debt service, and a landlord is entitled to a return. I'm not against people making
      money on their investments.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      But I want you to hold that number in your head while you read what comes next.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">Then look at what happened to the neighbourhood</h2>

    <div class="beat">
      <div class="n">1994</div>
      <h3>Nobody wanted this block.</h3>
      <p>
        Vacant storefronts. A shantytown two blocks away burned down the year we moved in, killing
        two people. The Columbia Street waterfront was cut off from the rest of Brooklyn by the BQE
        trench. That is <em>why</em> a developer couldn't sell condos here, and it is why the
        building ended up as low-income housing instead.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="beat">
      <div class="n">The next thirty years</div>
      <h3>We stayed. And the neighbourhood became beautiful.</h3>
      <p>
        Working people — hospital workers, an X-ray tech, nurses, a security guard, teachers, a
        chef, a union organizer, an Olympic gold medallist, essential workers this city applauded
        from its windows in 2020 — stayed here through all of it and built a community. Two of the
        warehouses on our own street were converted into luxury condos. Restaurants opened.
        Now people walk their dogs here after midnight.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>We are not bystanders to that transformation. We are the reason for it.</strong>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="beat hard">
      <div class="n">Now</div>
      <h3>And that is the argument for why we have to leave.</h3>
      <p>
        The building is worth a fortune. Our landlord's opening number was in the tens of millions —
        a figure with no relationship to what he paid, and every relationship to a neighbourhood
        that we made desirable while paying him rent.
      </p>
      <p>
        We are being priced out by an appreciation that <em>we created</em>, in a building the
        <em>public</em> paid to make affordable.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="pull">
      The subsidy was supposed to buy affordable housing.
      What it actually bought was thirty years of delay before the market took the building anyway —
      and it handed the owner an asset the public and the tenants had spent three decades making
      valuable.
    </div>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">This is where LIHTC and a land trust part company</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Now go back and look at Cooper Square. Their land is in a community land trust. It is
      <em>off the market</em>. When the neighbourhood around it gentrifies — and the Lower East
      Side gentrified ferociously — that appreciation cannot be captured and sold, because nobody
      owns the land for profit.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      The community's success does not become the community's eviction notice.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      At 63 Tiffany, it does. Same city. Same decades. Same gentrification.
      <strong>Different ownership structure, opposite outcome.</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      <a href="/community-ownership/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">See the two paths side by side →</a>
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">Which is why the right to buy is not enough on its own</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      I co-chaired the TOPA campaign. I organize for COPA. I want them passed, and I have watched
      the people fighting for them work themselves to the bone against an industry with better
      lawyers, better lobbyists, and bigger cheques.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      So this is not a criticism of the bills. It's what the people writing them already know, and
      say out loud themselves:
    </p>

    <div class="pull">
      A right of first refusal is a right to <em>be at the table</em>.
      It is not, by itself, the money to sit down.
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      New Economy Project — who convene the city's community land trusts and co-lead the COPA fight
      — put it plainly: CLTs <em>"also need real financial resources to make these purchases—which
      is why we need robust city and state funding."</em> They are right, and my building is the
      proof.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      The tenants want to buy. A nonprofit partner is willing. It is not a question of will.
      <strong>It is a question of price</strong> — and the price is set by a market whose value we
      created, with public money, over thirty years.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      So pass TOPA. Pass COPA. And then <strong>fund them like you meant it</strong>, and make
      affordability permanent so the speculative value never shows up to price us out in the first
      place. Those three things are one policy. Any one of them alone leaves buildings like mine
      exactly where we are.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">And the clock does not wait for the movement</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      I don't want to sound defeated, because the tenant movement in this state has been winning
      real things after decades of losing almost everything. It is organized, it is growing, and it
      is finally being taken seriously.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      But every year we spend building that power is a year in which more LIHTC agreements quietly
      run out. The expirations are not waiting for us to be ready. They are on a schedule that was
      set thirty years ago, and they arrive whether or not the coalition has the votes yet.
    </p>

    <div class="pull red">
      We are winning, and we are still losing buildings.
      Both of those things are true — and the second one has a deadline.
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      That is the whole argument of this website, and it is why I am in a hurry.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">So what would actually fix it</h2>
    <ul style="margin-top:18px;padding-left:22px">
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#243247">
        <strong>Fund acquisition at the real scale.</strong> The city relaunched its acquisition and
        rehab fund in April 2025 at <strong>$13 million</strong> — less than the asking price of a
        single Brooklyn building. A right to buy without money is a right to lose the auction politely.
      </li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#243247">
        <strong>Make affordability permanent from the start.</strong> If the restriction never
        expires, the speculative value never appears, and there is nothing to price us out with.
        This is what Vermont does. It is the only structural answer.
      </li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#243247">
        <strong>Recognise what the public already paid.</strong> When a building was made possible
        by public subsidy, the public's contribution should count for something at the moment of
        sale — through a restricted valuation, a recapture, or preservation financing that closes
        the gap. The taxpayer put money in. The taxpayer should not have to buy it back at retail.
      </li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#243247">
        <strong>Stop treating the exit as somebody else's problem.</strong> Every LIHTC deal has an
        ending. We have written forty years of them and never once written the ending down.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="pull">
      They subsidized a landlord to house us for thirty years.
      Then they let him sell the neighbourhood we built, at a price we can't pay,
      and called it the market working.
    </div>

    <div class="note" style="margin-top:36px">
      <b>On the numbers.</b>
      The purchase prices are public record — the $4m foreclosure auction was reported in the
      <em>New York Times</em>, and the 2010 sale is on file. The rent figures are my own, from my
      own apartment, and I have done the arithmetic myself. I am not publishing the current asking
      price, because negotiations are live and it isn't mine to publish. What I can tell you is that
      it bears no relationship to what anyone paid for this building, and every relationship to what
      we turned this neighbourhood into.
    </div>

  </div>
</main>

